@LBA2_PRODUCT_NAME@ @LBA2_VERSION_STRING@
====================================================

@LBA2_PRODUCT_DESCRIPTION@

This is a portable, statically-linked build. No installer, no package
manager, no system libraries beyond glibc. Drop @LBA2_EXECUTABLE_NAME@
anywhere and run.

If you want a desktop menu entry and icon, grab the AppImage release
artifact instead — that's what it's for. This tarball is the
"binary-only, scripting-friendly" alternative.


GAME DATA
---------

This fork doesn't include game data — you need a legitimate copy of
Little Big Adventure 2 / Twinsen's Odyssey from GOG, Steam, or your
original retail CD.

Easiest setup: run @LBA2_EXECUTABLE_NAME@ from a terminal. A folder
picker will open and ask you to point at your retail install — the
folder containing lba2.hqr (alongside music/, video/, vox/, etc., or
under a Common/ or CommonClassic/ subfolder for Steam/GOG re-releases).
Your choice is remembered, so subsequent launches skip the picker.

Alternative — drop @LBA2_EXECUTABLE_NAME@ directly into your existing
LBA2 install folder and run it from there. The engine auto-discovers
game data in the directory the binary is launched from (or in a "data"
/ "game" subfolder next to it), so the picker won't appear in that
case.

To re-pick later (e.g. switching between two installs):

    ./@LBA2_EXECUTABLE_NAME@ --pick-game-dir

Or skip the picker entirely with an explicit path:

    ./@LBA2_EXECUTABLE_NAME@ --game-dir /path/to/game
    LBA2_GAME_DIR=/path/to/game ./@LBA2_EXECUTABLE_NAME@

The remembered choice lives at:

    ~/.local/share/Twinsen/LBA2/last_game_dir.txt
    (or $XDG_DATA_HOME/Twinsen/LBA2/last_game_dir.txt if set)

Delete it to force the picker to re-appear on next launch.


RUNNING
-------

    ./@LBA2_EXECUTABLE_NAME@

If the folder picker doesn't open (common on minimal Linux setups and
WSL, where no dialog backend is installed), either install one:

    sudo apt install zenity          (Debian / Ubuntu / WSL)
    pacman -S zenity                 (Arch)
    dnf install zenity               (Fedora)

or skip the picker entirely by passing the path:

    ./@LBA2_EXECUTABLE_NAME@ --game-dir /path/to/game

If it still can't find game data, the log printed to stderr lists every
directory it tried.


